    <h1>CENTELLA ASIATICA</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201023/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-23"><time>2020-10-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | STYLE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A hall­mark of K-beauty, centella asiatica – nick­named cica – has been ris­ing steadily in pop­u­lar­ity in Western skin­care for its sooth­ing prop­er­ties.</p>
    <p>Known also as Asi­atic pen­ny­wort or tiger grass, this leafy medic­i­nal herb is of­ten used as a hero in­gre­di­ent for calm­ing in­flam­ma­tion and red­ness.</p>
    <p>While it first gained promi­nence in South Korean creams, cica is now found in many re­pair­ing serums, sheet masks and even acne treat­ments.</p>
    <p>The nat­u­ral in­gre­di­ent has an­tiox­i­dant prop­er­ties and has been found to be ben­e­fi­cial in speed­ing wound-heal­ing and re­pair­ing the skin bar­rier.</p>
    <p>TRY:</p>
    <p>1. AHC Pre­mium Cica 3 Com­plex Skin Fit Mask, $34.50 for five sheets</p>
    <p>2. Dr. G R.E.D Blem­ish Clear Quick Sooth­ing Pads, $36.90 3. CELLOOM Fo­cus on the Essence Serum, $59</p>

